paragraphs.text: %md ### MapR-DB Connector for Apache Spark Note: Before running this lab you have to complete Steps 1-3 to populate the MapR Database correctly The Spark MapR Database Connector enables users to perform complex SQL queries and updates on top of MapR-DB using a Spark Dataset, while applying critical techniques such as projection and filter pushdown, custom partitioning, and data locality. With MapR Database, a table is automatically partitioned into tablets across a cluster by key range, providing for scalable and fast reads and writes by row key. In this use case, the row key (the id) starts with the origin (destination airport codes), followed by the flightdate and carrier, so the table is automatically partitioned and sorted by the src, dst, date, and carrier. The Spark MapR Database Connector architecture has a connection object in every Spark Executor, allowing for distributed parallel writes, reads, or scans with MapR Database partitions.

Note: Before running this lab you have to complete Steps 1-3 to populate the MapR Database correctly

The Spark MapR Database Connector enables users to perform complex SQL queries and updates on top of MapR-DB using a Spark Dataset, while applying critical techniques such as projection and filter pushdown, custom partitioning, and data locality.

With MapR Database, a table is automatically partitioned into tablets across a cluster by key range, providing for scalable and fast reads and writes by row key.

In this use case, the row key (the id) starts with the origin (destination airport codes), followed by the flightdate and carrier, so the table is automatically partitioned and sorted by the src, dst, date, and carrier.

The Spark MapR Database Connector architecture has a connection object in every Spark Executor, allowing for distributed parallel writes, reads, or scans with MapR Database partitions.

%md
## Projection and Filter Pushdown into MapR Database
Below, we see the physical plan for a DataFrame query, with projection and filter pushdown. This means that the scanning of the src, dst, and depdelay columns and the filter on the depdelay column are pushed down into MapR Database, meaning that the scanning and filtering will take place in MapR Database before returning the data to Spark. Projection pushdown minimizes data transfer between MapR Database and the Spark engine by omitting unnecessary fields from table scans. It is especially beneficial when a table contains many columns. Filter pushdown improves performance by reducing the amount of data passed between MapR Database and the Spark engine when filtering data.

paragraphs.title: Calculate some more metrics
paragraphs.text:
val lp = df.select( "label", "prediction")
val counttotal = lp.count().toDouble
val correct = lp.filter($"label" === $"prediction").count().toDouble
val wrong = lp.filter(not($"label" === $"prediction")).count().toDouble
val truep =( lp.filter($"label" === 1.0).filter($"label" === $"prediction").count()) /counttotal
val truen = (lp.filter($"label" === 0.0).filter($"label" === $"prediction").count())/counttotal
val falsep = (lp.filter($"label" === 1.0).filter(not($"label" === $"prediction")).count())/counttotal
val falsen = (lp.filter($"label" === 0.0).filter(not($"label" === $"prediction")).count())/counttotal
val ratioWrong=wrong/counttotal
val ratioCorrect=correct/counttotal
